defaultcontempt of court 
defaultn
defaultor for
default default
defaulting on fines.
default  The Court is also incorrect to descr
defaultibe the ban on prisoner voting a
defaults disproportionate.  Under the law as it stands, every prisoner over the age of 18 and who is a British national will regain the right to vote once he or she is released from prison.  The length of time for which each prisoner loses the vote is lost is therefore directly proportionate to the seriousness of the crime he or she has committed, as the length of the voting ban mirrors exactly the 
defaultlength of the sentence served.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe 
defaultCourt’s 
defaultsecond 
defaultargument, that UK prisoners are not informed in court, at sentencing, that they will lose the right to vote, can be addressed easily through a minor ch
defaultange to sentencing guidelines requiring judges to inform those given a custodial sentence that they will lose the right to vote for the duration of their imprisonment.  There is no need to lift the ban on prisoner voting in order to address this issue.
default&#xa0;
